\title{Invariant subsets}
\author{alex-nelson}
\import{notation}
\date{2025-12-16}
\taxon{definition}

\p{Let #{G} be a [[gr-000G]] and #{X} be a set. Suppose #{G} [acts](gr-004Y) on #{X}. Let #{Y\subset X}. We say #{Y} is an \define{Invariant Subset} of #{X} if #{G\cdot Y\subset Y}, i.e., for each #{y\in Y} and #{g\in G} we have #{g\cdot y\in Y}.}
\p{If there is some ambiguity about which group #{Y} is invariant with respect to, we say #{Y} is \define{#{G}-Invariant} (or \define{Stable under #{G}} or \define{#{G}-Stable}).}

\rmk{This should evoke vague memories from intermediate linear algebra about [[vectsp-001P]]s.}